{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "The former estimates the stopping criteria based on the derivation of an estimate of the total number of relevant papers within an initial training set and is considered more reliable than the latter (Cormack & Grossman, 2016; van Haastrecht et al., 2021).",
    "However, its practical application is limited.",
    "In contrast, heuristic approaches, including time-based, data-driven, and mixed-data strategies, are commonly used to determine when to stop reviewing (e.g., Guan et al., 2023; Huang et al., 2022; Scherer & Campos, 2022; Zhang et al., 2023).",
    "Time-based approaches involve stopping the review after reviewing a certain number of abstracts (Wallace et al., 2010).",
    "In contrast, datadriven approaches stop after identifying a certain number of consecutive irrelevant abstracts (Ros et al., 2017)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
